scientific theory. May 27]</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Scientific American\">[http://www.sciam.com/article.cfm?articleID=000656C3-8F00-1CDA-B4A8809EC588EEDF Relative Abundance of 1,175 Plant Species within a Borneo Plot]</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Volkov2003\">{{cite journal |title=Neutral theory and relative species abundance in ecology |url=https://repository.si.edu/bitstream/handle/10088/2249/Volkov_Banavar_Hubbell_and_Maritan.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y |journal=Nature |date=2003-08-28 |issn=0028-0836 |pages=1035\u20131037 |volume=424 |issue=6952 |doi=10.1038/nature01883 |first=Igor |last=Volkov |first2=Jayanth R. |last2=Banavar |first3=Stephen P. |last3=Hubbell |first4=Amos |last4=Maritan |pmid=12944964|arxiv=q-bio/0504018 |bibcode=2003Natur.424.1035V }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Wootton2005\">{{cite journal |last1=Wootton |first1=J.T. |title=Field parameterization and experimental test of the neutral theory of biodiversity |journal=Nature |volume=433 | pages=309\u2013312 | year=2005 |pmid=15662423 |doi=10.1038/nature03211 |bibcode=2005Natur.433..309W |issue=7023}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Vallade2003\">{{cite journal |last=Vallade |first=M. |author2=Houchmandzadeh, B. |title=Analytical solution of a neutral model of biodiversity |journal=Phys. Rev. E |volume=68 |issue=61902 |year=2003 |doi=10.1103/PhysRevE.68.061902 |pmid=14754229 |pages=061902 |bibcode =2003PhRvE..68f1902V|url=https://hal.archives-ouvertes.fr/hal-00976654/document }}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n*{{cite journal|last=Gilbert|first=B |author2=Lechowicz MJ |year=2004|title=Neutrality, niches, and dispersal in a temperate forest understory|journal=PNAS|volume=101|pages=7651\u20137656|doi=10.1073/pnas.0400814101|pmid=15128948|issue=20|pmc=419661|bibcode = 2004PNAS..101.7651G }}\n* {{cite journal|author=Leigh E.G. (Jr) | year=2007| title=Neutral theory: a historical perspective| journal=[[Journal of Evolutionary Biology]] |volume=20 |pages=2075\u20132091| doi=10.1111/j.1420-9101.2007.01410.x|pmid=17956380|issue=6|url=http://si-pddr.si.edu/dspace/bitstream/10088/6669/1/Leigh0305neutral_theory_a_historic.pdf}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Preston|first=F. W.|title=The Canonical Distribution of Commonness and Rarity: Part I|journal=Ecology|volume=43|issue=2|pages=185\u2013215|year=1962|doi=10.2307/1931976|publisher=Ecology, Vol. 43, No. 2|jstor=1931976}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Pueyo |first=S. |author2=He, F. |author3=Zillio, T. |year=2007 |title=The maximum entropy formalism and the idiosyncratic theory of biodiversity |journal=Ecology Letters |volume=10 |pages=1017\u20131028 |doi=10.1111/j.1461-0248.2007.01096.x |pmid=17692099 |issue=11 |pmc=2121135 }}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.sciam.com/article.cfm?articleID=000D401A-8D9D-1CDA-B4A8809EC588EEDF Scientific American Interview with Steve Hubbell]\n* [http://finzi.psych.upenn.edu/R/library/untb/html/untb.package.html R package for implementing UNTB]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130806083430/http://news.cell.com/discussions/trends-in-ecology-and-evolution/ecological-neutral-theory-useful-model-or-statement-of-ignorance \"Ecological neutral theory: useful model or statement of ignorance?\" in Cell Press Discussions]\n\n{{modelling ecosystems|expanded=other}}\n\n[[Category:Biodiversity]]\n[[Category:Ecological theories]]\n[[Category:Theoretical ecology]]\n", "name_user": "L T T H U", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eStochastic modelling of species abundances under the UNTB:plural", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unified_neutral_theory_of_biodiversity"}
{"title_page": "Whipped cream", "text_new": "{{other uses}}\n{{redirect|Whipping cream|the definitions of \"whipping cream\" used in various countries|Cream#Types}}\n{{Infobox prepared food\n| name             = Whipped cream\n| image            = Kakao mit Sahne 281104.jpg\n| image_size       = 250px\n| caption          = A cup of [[hot chocolate]] topped with whipped cream from a pressurized can.\n| alternate_name   = \n| country          = \n| region           = \n| creator          = \n| course           = \n| type             = [[Cream]]\n| served           = \n| main_ingredient  = Cream\n| variations       = Added [[sugar]] and other flavorings, such as [[vanilla]]\n| calories         = \n| other            = \n}}\n[[Image:Pumpkin Pie.JPG|thumb|250px|A slice of [[pumpkin pie]] topped with a whipped cream rose]]\n[[Image:Cr\u00e8me Chantilly.jpg|thumb|250px|''Cr\u00e8me Chantilly'']]\n\nWassup computer dude how\u2019s your day going? '''Whipped cream''' is a culinary [[colloid]] produced when [[cream]] is aerated by one of two processes: mechanical agitation with a high-speed blade or whip, or injecting a gas under high pressure which expands rapidly when released from pressurized containment. It is often sweetened and sometimes flavored with [[vanilla]]. Whipped cream is also called '''Chantilly cream''' or '''Cr\u00e8me chantilly''' ({{IPA-fr|k\u0281\u025bm \u0283\u0251\u0303tiji|pron}}).\n\n== Fat content==\nThe typical fat content of cream used for whipping is high as fat globules contribute to forming a stable structure surrounding and stabilizing air bubbles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uoguelph.ca/foodscience/book-page/whipped-cream-structure|title=Whipped Cream Structure {{!}} Food Science|website=www.uoguelph.ca|access-date=2020-01-04}}</ref>. The typical fat content for whipping cream is between 30%-36% milkfat. Other components include water at 62.9-57.3% and proteins at 2.5-2.2%.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Aggarwal|first=M. L.|date=June 19, 1974|title=Ultra-Pasteurization of Whipping Cream|url=https://jfoodprotection.org/doi/pdf/10.4315/0022-2747-38.1.36|journal=Journal of Food and Milk Technology|volume=38|pages=36-38|via=}}</ref>\n\nDuring whipping, partially coalesced fat molecules create a stabilized network which traps air bubbles.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Viet|last2=Cua|title=Effect of thermal treatment on physical properties and stability of whipping and whipped cream|url=|journal=Journal of Food Engineering|volume= 163|doi=10.1016/j.jfoodeng.2015.04.026|pages=32\u201336|year=2015}}</ref> The resulting colloid is roughly double the volume of the original cream. If, however, the whipping is continued, the fat droplets will stick together destroying the colloid and forming [[butter]].  Lower-fat cream (or milk) does not whip well, while higher-fat cream produces a more stable foam.<ref name=\"mcgee\"/>\n\n==Methods of whipping==\n<!--[[Whipping siphon]] redirects directly here.-->\nCream is usually mechanically whipped with a [[whisk]], an electric hand [[mixer (cooking)|mixer]], or a [[food processor]]. Results are best when the equipment and ingredients are cold.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bonappetit.com/test-kitchen/common-mistakes/article/whipped-cream-common-mistakes|title=Whip it Real Good: How to Make Whipped Cream at Home|first=Rochelle|last=Bilow|date=|website=bonappetit.com}}</ref> The bubbles in the mechanically whipped cream immediately start to pop, and the whipped cream begins to liquefy. Thus mechanically whipped cream has a useful lifetime of one to two hours. Many 19th-century recipes recommend adding [[gum tragacanth]] to stabilize whipped cream, while a few include [[whipped egg whites]].<ref name=\"dubois\"/>  Various other substances, including [[gelatin]] and [[E450 (food additive)|diphosphate]], are used in commercial [[Stabiliser (food)|stabilizers]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Wayne Gisslen|title=Professional Baking|year=2008|ISBN=0471783498|p=264}}</ref><ref>Alan Imeson, ed., ''Food Stabilisers, Thickeners and Gelling Agents'', 2011, {{ISBN|1444360337}}, ''passim''</ref><ref>Rose Levy Beranbaum, ''The Pie and Pastry Bible'', 2009, {{ISBN|1439130876}}, p. 550</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Dr. Oetker Whip It|website=Dr. Oetker|url=http://www.oetker.ca/ca-en/our-products/dr-oetker-whip-it/dr-oetker-whip-it.html}}</ref>\n\nWhipped cream may also be made instantly as needed, in two ways: from a retail can, or in a [[soda siphon|'''whipping siphon''']]. Cream is placed into the siphon, and a [[whipped-cream charger]] is inserted into its holder in the siphon. When the top is screwed on the charger is automatically opened, and the pressurized gas contained therein is released to dissolve into the cream. Typically the gas is [[nitrous oxide]], as [[carbon dioxide]] tends to give a sour taste.<ref name=\"lange\"/> The nitrous oxide gas dissolves in the butterfat under pressure. When the pressure is released bubbles are produced, and thus the cream is instantly whipped. \n\n== Flavorings ==\n\nWhipped cream is often flavored with sugar, [[vanilla]], [[coffee]], [[chocolate]], [[Orange (fruit)|orange]], and so on.<ref>Jules Gouff\u00e9e ''et al.'', ''Le livre de p\u00e2tisserie'', 1873 p. [https://archive.org/details/lelivredepatisse00gouf/page/138 138]</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{Rquote|right|Les mousses se font avec de la cr\u00eame bien douce & peu \u00e9paisse; on la fouette, ce qui la fait mousser, & c'est de cette mousse qu'on fait usage: on peut lui donner tel go\u00fbt que l'on veut, aromates, fleurs, fruits, vins, ou liqueurs.\n<hr>\nMousses are made with sweet cream, not very thick; one whips it, which makes it foam, and it is this foam that one uses: one may give it whatever flavor one wants, with aromatics, flours, fruits, wines, or liqueurs.|M. Emy, 1768<ref name=\"emy\"/>}}\nWhipped cream, often sweetened and aromatised, was popular in the 16th century,<ref name=\"scully\"/> with recipes in the writings of [[Cristoforo di Messisbugo]] ([[Ferrara]], 1549),<ref>Michelle Berriedale-Johnson, ''Festive Feasts Cookbook'' (British Museum), 2004, {{ISBN|0-299-19510-4}}, [https://books.google.com/books?id=qiDBvjhUqnUC&pg=PA33 p. 33], citing Messisbugo's ''Banchetti, composizioni di vivande e apparecchio generale''</ref> [[Bartolomeo Scappi]] ([[Rome]], 1570),<ref name=\"scully\">Terence Scully, trans., ''The Opera of Bartolomeo Scappi (1570): L'arte et prudenza d'un maestro Cuoco; The Art and Craft of a Master Cook'', 2008, {{ISBN|0-8020-9624-7}}, [https://books.google.com/books?id=GrvhZvK5pCgC&pg=PA105 p. 105, note 2.39], with many menus including \"neve di latte servita con zuccaro sopra\" 'milk snow with sugar on top', [https://books.google.com/books?id=GrvhZvK5pCgC&q=%22neve+di+latte%22 ''passim'']</ref> and [[Lancelot de Casteau]] ([[Li\u00e8ge]], 1604).<ref>''Ouverture de cuisine'',  \"Pour faire neige\", p. 123 [http://www.uni-giessen.de/gloning/tx/ouv3.htm transcription]</ref> It was called milk or cream snow (''neve di latte'', ''neige de lait'', ''neige de cr\u00e8me'').<ref>''[[Tr\u00e9sor de la langue fran\u00e7aise]]'' [http://www.cnrtl.fr/definition/neige ''s.v.'' ''neige'' \u00c9tymologie B.2] (1552 quotation)</ref>  A 1545 English recipe, \"A Dyschefull of Snow\", includes whipped egg whites as well, and is flavored with [[rosewater]] and [[sugar]].<ref>Catherine Frances Frere, ''Prepere newe Booke of Cokerye'', 1545 (modern edition 1913) -- cited in Scully</ref>  (''cf.'' [[Snow cream#The cream-based dessert|snow cream]]) In these recipes, and until the end of the 19th century, naturally separated cream is whipped, typically with [[willow]] or [[Juncaceae|rush]] branches, and the resulting foam on the surface would from time to time be skimmed off and drained, a process taking an hour or more.<ref name=\"mcgee\">Harold McGee, ''On Food and Cooking'', p. 32</ref> By the end of the 19th century, [[separator (milk)|centrifuge-separated]], high-fat cream made it much faster and easier to make whipped cream.\n\nThe French name ''cr\u00e8me fouett\u00e9e'' 'whipped cream' is attested in 1629,<ref>[[Jean-Louis Guez de Balzac]], ''Lettres de Phyllarque \u00e0 Ariste'' [https://books.google.com/books?id=zW_PCX1pb80C&pg=PA370&dq=%22cr%C3%A8me+fouett%C3%A9e%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=EzsFUbXAKcfg0gGrj4CYDg&ved=0CDkQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q&f=false full text]</ref> and the English name \"whipped cream\" in 1673.<ref>{{Cite OED|whipped|id =228422}}</ref> The name \"snow cream\" continued to be used in the 17th century.<ref>''Dictionarium Rusticum, Urbanicum & Botanicum'', 1726, ''s.v.'' 'Syllabub' [https://books.google.com/books?id=v2FJAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA1-PT296 full text]</ref><ref>Sarah Harrison, ''The house-keeper's pocket-book, and compleat family cook'', 1749, p. 173. [https://books.google.com/books?id=3IcEAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA173 full text]</ref>\n\nVarious desserts consisting of whipped cream in pyramidal shapes with coffee, liqueurs, chocolate, fruits, and so on either in the mixture or poured on top were called ''cr\u00e8me en mousse'' 'cream in a foam', ''cr\u00e8me fouett\u00e9e'', ''cr\u00e8me mousseuse'' 'foamy cream', ''mousse'' 'foam',<ref name=\"emy\">M. Emy (officier), '' L'Art de bien faire les glaces d'office... avec un trait\u00e9 sur les mousses'', Paris, 1768 [https://books.google.com/books?id=qDZdAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA222 p. 222]</ref><ref>Alexandre-Balthazar-Laurent [[Grimod de La Reyni\u00e8re]], ''N\u00e9o-Physiologie du gout par order alphab\u00e9tique ou Dictionnaire g\u00e9n\u00e9rale de la cuisine fran\u00e7aise'', 1839, [https://books.google.com/books?id=ts9QAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA184 p. 184]</ref> and ''fromage \u00e0 la Chantilly'' 'Chantilly-style molded cream', as early as 1768.<ref name=\"chev\">Jim Chevallier, ''A History of the Food of Paris: From Roast Mammoth to Steak Frites'', 2018, {{isbn|1442272821}}, p. 195</ref><ref>\"Tante Marie\", ''La V\u00e9ritable cuisine de famille, comprenant 1.000 recettes et 500 menus'', 18??, [https://books.google.com/books?id=5A80_xF0vHUC&pg=PA296 p. 296] \"Cr\u00e8me fouett\u00e9e (ou Fromage \u00e0 la Chantilly)\"</ref><ref>Mrs. Beeton, ''The book of household management'', 1888, [https://books.google.com/books?id=otoAAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA927 p. 927]</ref>  Modern [[mousse]]s, including [[mousse au chocolat]], are a continuation of this tradition.\n\nCream whipped in a whipping siphon with nitrous oxide was invented in the 1930s by both Charles Getz, working with [[G. Frederick Smith]],<ref>Charles Getz, \"Process of making aerated food products\", U.S. Patent 2294172A, filed 26 September 1935, issued 25 August 1942 [http://www.google.com/patents/US2294172 full text]; also U.S. Patent 2435682 (continuation in part)</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=George Frederick Smith (1891-1976)|website=Chemistry at Illinois|publisher=University of Illinois|url=http://www.chemistry.illinois.edu/about/illini_chemists/smith.html|accessdate=2014-02-27|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131104160841/http://www.chemistry.illinois.edu/about/illini_chemists/smith.html|archivedate=2013-11-04}}</ref> and Marshall Reinecke.<ref>Marshall C. Reinecke, \"Device for producing aerated expanded food products\", U.S. Patent 2120297A, filed 15 August 1935, issued 14 June 1938 [http://www.google.com/patents/US2120297 full text]</ref> Both filed patents, which were later litigated. The Getz patents were originally deemed invalid, but were upheld on appeal.<ref name=\"lange\">Aeration Processes, Inc. ''v.'' Lange ''et al.'', 196 F.2d 981, 93 USPQ 332, United States Court of Appeals Eighth Circuit, May 20, 1952.</ref>\n\n==Cr\u00e8me Chantilly==\n\n''Cr\u00e8me Chantilly'' is another name for whipped cream. The difference between \"whipped cream\" and \"cr\u00e8me Chantilly\" is not systematic. Some authors distinguish between the two, with cr\u00e8me Chantilly being sweetened, and whipped cream not.<ref>{{cite book|chapter=Cr\u00e8me fouett\u00e9e et cr\u00e8me Chantilly|editor=Robert J. Courtine|title=Curnonsky: Cuisine et Vins de France|publisher=Larousse|year=1974|p=535}}</ref> However, most authors treat the two as synonyms,<ref name=\"robert\">{{cite book|title=[[Petit Robert|Le Petit Robert]]|year=1972|chapter=''Cr\u00e8me fouett\u00e9e'', dite aussi ''cr\u00e8me Chantilly''}}</ref> with both being sweetened,<ref name=\"grande\">''[[La Grande Encyclop\u00e9die]]'' (1902)</ref><ref>''[[Tr\u00e9sor de la langue fran\u00e7aise]]'', [http://www.cnrtl.fr/definition/cr\u00e8me ''s.v.'' cr\u00e8me]</ref> neither being sweetened,<ref name=\"dubois\">\u00c9mile Bernard Urbain Dubois, ''La Cuisine classique: \u00e9tudes pratiques, raisonn\u00e9es et d\u00e9monstratives de l'Ecole fran\u00e7aise appliqu\u00e9e au service \u00e0 la russe'', 1868, [https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_A7DX5_x_hrAC/page/n144 p. 122]: \"La chantilly n'est autre chose que la cr\u00e8me double, amen\u00e9e \u00e0 consistance, et rendue mousseuse par le travail du fouet et l'action de l'air.\"</ref><ref name=\"bocuse\">[[Paul Bocuse]], ''La cuisine du march\u00e9'' (1980), p. 414: \"Cr\u00e8me Chantilly (cr\u00e8me fouett\u00e9e)\"</ref> or treating sweetening as optional.<ref name=\"saint-ange\">''[[La cuisine de Madame Saint-Ange]]'' (1927), p. 916''f'': \"Cr\u00e8me fouett\u00e9e dite \u00ab cr\u00e8me Chantilly \u00bb... Selon le cas, on ajoute du sucre en poudre, vanill\u00e9 ou non, dans la cr\u00e8me fouett\u00e9e.\"</ref><ref>Julia Child ''et al.'', ''Mastering the Art of French Cooking'', defines ''Cr\u00e8me Chantilly'' as \"lightly beaten cream\", then refers to it as \"whipped cream\".  With added sugar or flavorings,  she calls it \"Flavored whipped cream\" ('''I''':580). In volume 2, one recipe for ''cr\u00e8me Chantilly'' is unsweetened ('''II''':422), another is sweetened ('''II''':450).</ref> Many authors use only one of the two names (for the sweetened or unsweetened version), so it is not clear if they distinguish the two.<ref>[[Larousse du XIXe]] (1878) et le [[Littr\u00e9]] (1872) mention only whipped (fouett\u00e9e); le [[Larousse Gastronomique]] (1938) mentions only Chantilly</ref>\n\nThe invention of cr\u00e8me Chantilly is often credited incorrectly, and without evidence, to [[Fran\u00e7ois Vatel]], ''[[ma\u00eetre d'h\u00f4tel]]'' at the [[Ch\u00e2teau de Chantilly]] in the mid-17th century.<ref>{{cite book|author=Stephen Shapiro|chapter=Roland Joff\u00e9's ''Vatel''|editor=Anne L. Birberick|editor2=Russell Ganim|title=Modern Perspectives on the Early Modern: Temps recherch\u00e9, temps retrouv\u00e9|year=2005|ISBN=1-886365-54-7|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=QtjJxJoXx5MC&pg=PA84 84]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.domainedechantilly.com/domaine-de-chantilly/cr%C3%A8me-chantilly/histoire-de-la-cr%C3%A8me-chantilly|title=Histoire de la Cr\u00e8me Chantilly|website=Domaine de Chantilly|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130416042751/http://www.domainedechantilly.com/domaine-de-chantilly/cr%C3%A8me-chantilly/histoire-de-la-cr%C3%A8me-chantilly|archive-date=2013-04-16}}</ref> But the name Chantilly is first connected with whipped cream in the mid-18th century,<ref>{{cite book|chapter=Fromage \u00e0 la chantilly glac\u00e9|language=fr|trans-chapter=Ice cream whipped cheese|editor=[[Menon (cookbook author)|Menon]]|title=Les soupers de la cour|trans-title=Court suppers|year=1755|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=dTI7AAAAcAAJ&pg=PA313&lpg=PA313 313-314]}}</ref> around the time that the [[Baronne d'Oberkirch]] praised the \"cream\" served at a lunch at the [[Hameau de Chantilly]]&mdash;but did not say what exactly it was, or call it Chantilly cream.<ref>{{cite book|title=M\u00e9moires de la baronne d'Oberkirch|volume=2|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=AMdCAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA112 112]|chapter=Jamais je n'ai mang\u00e9 d'aussi bonne cr\u00e8me, aussi app\u00e9tissante et aussi bien appr\u00eat\u00e9e|quote=I have never eaten such good cream, so appetising and so well prepared}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.institut-de-france.fr/minisite/tables/71_la_naissance_de_la_creme_chantilly.html|title=Naissance de la cr\u00e8me Chantilly|work=Tables princi\u00e8res \u00e0 Chantilly, du XVIIe au XIXe si\u00e8cle|language=fr|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110613140832/http://www.institut-de-france.fr/minisite/tables/71_la_naissance_de_la_creme_chantilly.html|archive-date=2011-06-13}} {{cite book|location=[[Mus\u00e9e Cond\u00e9]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081115004842/http://www.chateaudechantilly.com/pdf/DP2_tables_princieres.pdf|archive-date=2008-11-15|url=http://www.chateaudechantilly.com/pdf/DP2_tables_princieres.pdf|title=Exposition du 16 septembre 2006 au 8 janvier 2007 \u2014 Tables princi\u00e8res \u00e0 Chantilly, du XVIIe au XIXe si\u00e8cle|language=fr|trans-title=Exhibition from September 16, 2006 to January 8, 2007 \u2014 Princely tables in Chantilly, from the 17th to the 19th century|publisher=Fondation pour la sauvegarde et le d\u00e9veloppement du domaine de Chantilly}}</ref>\n\nThe names \"cr\u00e8me Chantilly\", \"cr\u00e8me de Chantilly\", \"cr\u00e8me \u00e0 la Chantilly\", or \"cr\u00e8me fouett\u00e9e \u00e0 la Chantilly\" only become common in the 19th century. In 1806, the first edition of Viard's ''[[Le Cuisinier Imp\u00e9rial|Cuisinier Imp\u00e9rial]]'' mentions neither \"whipped\" nor \"Chantilly\" cream,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sI4EAAAAYAAJ|title=Le cuisinier imp\u00e9rial, ou, L'art de faire la cuisine et la p\u00e2tisserie pour toutes les fortunes: avec diff\u00e9rentes recettes d'office et de fruits confits, et la mani\u00e8re de servir une table depuis vingt jusqu'\u00e0 soixante couverts|first=A.|last=Viard|date=1806|publisher=Barba|via=Google Books}}</ref> but the 1820 edition mentions both.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_6B5fVHfmd8kC|title=Le cuisinier royal: ou l'Art de faire la cuisine, la patisserie et tout ce qui concerne l'office, pour toutes les fortunes|first1=A.|last1=Viard|last2=Fouret|date=1820|publisher=J.-N. Barba|via=Internet Archive}}</ref>\n\nThe name ''Chantilly'' was probably used because the ch\u00e2teau had become a symbol of refined food.<ref>[[Alan Davidson (food writer)|Alan Davidson]], ''[[The Oxford Companion to Food]]'', ''s.v.'' 'cream'.</ref>\n\n==Imitation whipped cream==\nImitations of whipped cream, often sold under the name '''whipped topping''' or '''squirty cream''', are commercially available. They may be used to avoid [[dairy]] ingredients, to provide extended shelf life, or to reduce the price (although some popular brands cost twice as much as whipped cream).<ref>{{cite web|author=Patrick Di Justo|title=Cool Whip|work=[[Wired Magazine|Wired]]|date=April 24, 2007|url=https://www.wired.com/wired/archive/15.05/st_coolwhip.html}}</ref>\n\nArtificial whipped topping normally contains some mixture of [[partially hydrogenated]] oil, sweeteners, water, and stabilizers and emulsifiers added to prevent [[Syneresis (chemistry)|syneresis]].\n\nIt may be sold frozen in plastic tubs (''e.g.'', [[Cool Whip]]), or in aerosol containers or in liquid form in cartons, reminiscent of real whipping cream.\n\n==Uses==\nWhipped cream or ''cr\u00e8me Chantilly'' is a popular topping for fruit and [[dessert]]s such as pie, [[ice cream]] (especially [[sundae]]s), cupcakes, cakes, [[milkshake]]s, [[waffle]]s, [[hot chocolate]], [[cheesecake]]s, [[Jello]] and [[pudding]]s. It is also [[List of coffee drinks#Coffee or espresso with whipped cream|served on coffee]], especially in the [[Viennese coffee house]] tradition, where coffee with whipped cream is known as ''Melange mit Schlagobers''. Whipped cream is used as an ingredient in many desserts, for example as a filling for [[profiterole]]s and [[layer cake]]s.<ref>{{cite book|author=Wayne Gisslen|title=Professional Baking|year=2012|ISBN=1118254368|p=260}}</ref>\n\nIt is often piped onto a dish using a [[pastry bag]] to create decorative shapes.\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Food}}\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Alcohol-infused whipped cream]]\n* [[Dream Whip]]{{spaced ndash}} a powdered dessert topping mix\n* ''[[Schlagobers]]''{{spaced ndash}} [[Richard Strauss]]' \"Whipped Cream\" ballet\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Dairy products]]\n[[Category:Desserts]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses}}\n{{redirect|Whipping cream|the definitions of \"whipping cream\" used in various countries|Cream#Types}}\n{{Infobox prepared food\n| name             = Whipped cream\n| image            = Kakao mit Sahne 281104.jpg\n| image_size       = 250px\n| caption          = A cup of [[hot chocolate]] topped with whipped cream from a pressurized can.\n| alternate_name   = \n| country          = \n| region           = \n| creator          = \n| course           = \n| type             = [[Cream]]\n| served           = \n| main_ingredient  = Cream\n| variations       = Added [[sugar]] and other flavorings, such as [[vanilla]]\n| calories         = \n| other            = \n}}\n[[Image:Pumpkin Pie.JPG|thumb|250px|A slice of [[pumpkin pie]] topped with a whipped cream rose]]\n[[Image:Cr\u00e8me Chantilly.jpg|thumb|250px|''Cr\u00e8me Chantilly'']]\n\n'''Whipped cream''' is a culinary [[colloid]] produced when [[cream]] is aerated by one of two processes: mechanical agitation with a high-speed blade or whip, or injecting a gas under high pressure which expands rapidly when released from pressurized containment. It is often sweetened and sometimes flavored with [[vanilla]]. Whipped cream is also called '''Chantilly cream''' or '''Cr\u00e8me chantilly''' ({{IPA-fr|k\u0281\u025bm \u0283\u0251\u0303tiji|pron}}).\n\n== Fat content==\nThe typical fat content of cream used for whipping is high as fat globules contribute to forming a stable structure surrounding and stabilizing air bubbles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uoguelph.ca/foodscience/book-page/whipped-cream-structure|title=Whipped Cream Structure {{!}} Food Science|website=www.uoguelph.ca|access-date=2020-01-04}}</ref>. The typical fat content for whipping cream is between 30%-36% milkfat. Other components include water at 62.9-57.3% and proteins at 2.5-2.2%.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Aggarwal|first=M. L.|date=June 19, 1974|title=Ultra-Pasteurization of Whipping Cream|url=https://jfoodprotection.org/doi/pdf/10.4315/0022-2747-38.1.36|journal=Journal of Food and Milk Technology|volume=38|pages=36-38|via=}}</ref>\n\nDuring whipping, partially coalesced fat molecules create a stabilized network which traps air bubbles.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Viet|last2=Cua|title=Effect of thermal treatment on physical properties and stability of whipping and whipped cream|url=|journal=Journal of Food Engineering|volume= 163|doi=10.1016/j.jfoodeng.2015.04.026|pages=32\u201336|year=2015}}</ref> The resulting colloid is roughly double the volume of the original cream. If, however, the whipping is continued, the fat droplets will stick together destroying the colloid and forming [[butter]].  Lower-fat cream (or milk) does not whip well, while higher-fat cream produces a more stable foam.<ref name=\"mcgee\"/>\n\n==Methods of whipping==\n<!--[[Whipping siphon]] redirects directly here.-->\nCream is usually mechanically whipped with a [[whisk]], an electric hand [[mixer (cooking)|mixer]], or a [[food processor]]. Results are best when the equipment and ingredients are cold.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bonappetit.com/test-kitchen/common-mistakes/article/whipped-cream-common-mistakes|title=Whip it Real Good: How to Make Whipped Cream at Home|first=Rochelle|last=Bilow|date=|website=bonappetit.com}}</ref> The bubbles in the mechanically whipped cream immediately start to pop, and the whipped cream begins to liquefy. Thus mechanically whipped cream has a useful lifetime of one to two hours. Many 19th-century recipes recommend adding [[gum tragacanth]] to stabilize whipped cream, while a few include [[whipped egg whites]].<ref name=\"dubois\"/>  Various other substances, including [[gelatin]] and [[E450 (food additive)|diphosphate]], are used in commercial [[Stabiliser (food)|stabilizers]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Wayne Gisslen|title=Professional Baking|year=2008|ISBN=0471783498|p=264}}</ref><ref>Alan Imeson, ed., ''Food Stabilisers, Thickeners and Gelling Agents'', 2011, {{ISBN|1444360337}}, ''passim''</ref><ref>Rose Levy Beranbaum, ''The Pie and Pastry Bible'', 2009, {{ISBN|1439130876}}, p. 550</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Dr. Oetker Whip It|website=Dr. Oetker|url=http://www.oetker.ca/ca-en/our-products/dr-oetker-whip-it/dr-oetker-whip-it.html}}</ref>\n\nWhipped cream may also be made instantly as needed, in two ways: from a retail can, or in a [[soda siphon|'''whipping siphon''']]. Cream is placed into the siphon, and a [[whipped-cream charger]] is inserted into its holder in the siphon. When the top is screwed on the charger is automatically opened, and the pressurized gas contained therein is released to dissolve into the cream. Typically the gas is [[nitrous oxide]], as [[carbon dioxide]] tends to give a sour taste.<ref name=\"lange\"/> The nitrous oxide gas dissolves in the butterfat under pressure. When the pressure is released bubbles are produced, and thus the cream is instantly whipped. \n\n== Flavorings ==\n\nWhipped cream is often flavored with sugar, [[vanilla]], [[coffee]], [[chocolate]], [[Orange (fruit)|orange]], and so on.<ref>Jules Gouff\u00e9e ''et al.'', ''Le livre de p\u00e2tisserie'', 1873 p. [https://archive.org/details/lelivredepatisse00gouf/page/138 138]</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{Rquote|right|Les mousses se font avec de la cr\u00eame bien douce & peu \u00e9paisse; on la fouette, ce qui la fait mousser, & c'est de cette mousse qu'on fait usage: on peut lui donner tel go\u00fbt que l'on veut, aromates, fleurs, fruits, vins, ou liqueurs.\n<hr>\nMousses are made with sweet cream, not very thick; one whips it, which makes it foam, and it is this foam that one uses: one may give it whatever flavor one wants, with aromatics, flours, fruits, wines, or liqueurs.|M. Emy, 1768<ref name=\"emy\"/>}}\nWhipped cream, often sweetened and aromatised, was popular in the 16th century,<ref name=\"scully\"/> with recipes in the writings of [[Cristoforo di Messisbugo]] ([[Ferrara]], 1549),<ref>Michelle Berriedale-Johnson, ''Festive Feasts Cookbook'' (British Museum), 2004, {{ISBN|0-299-19510-4}}, [https://books.google.com/books?id=qiDBvjhUqnUC&pg=PA33 p. 33], citing Messisbugo's ''Banchetti, composizioni di vivande e apparecchio generale''</ref> [[Bartolomeo Scappi]] ([[Rome]], 1570),<ref name=\"scully\">Terence Scully, trans., ''The Opera of Bartolomeo Scappi (1570): L'arte et prudenza d'un maestro Cuoco; The Art and Craft of a Master Cook'', 2008, {{ISBN|0-8020-9624-7}}, [https://books.google.com/books?id=GrvhZvK5pCgC&pg=PA105 p. 105, note 2.39], with many menus including \"neve di latte servita con zuccaro sopra\" 'milk snow with sugar on top', [https://books.google.com/books?id=GrvhZvK5pCgC&q=%22neve+di+latte%22 ''passim'']</ref> and [[Lancelot de Casteau]] ([[Li\u00e8ge]], 1604).<ref>''Ouverture de cuisine'',  \"Pour faire neige\", p. 123 [http://www.uni-giessen.de/gloning/tx/ouv3.htm transcription]</ref> It was called milk or cream snow (''neve di latte'', ''neige de lait'', ''neige de cr\u00e8me'').<ref>''[[Tr\u00e9sor de la langue fran\u00e7aise]]'' [http://www.cnrtl.fr/definition/neige ''s.v.'' ''neige'' \u00c9tymologie B.2] (1552 quotation)</ref>  A 1545 English recipe, \"A Dyschefull of Snow\", includes whipped egg whites as well, and is flavored with [[rosewater]] and [[sugar]].<ref>Catherine Frances Frere, ''Prepere newe Booke of Cokerye'', 1545 (modern edition 1913) -- cited in Scully</ref>  (''cf.'' [[Snow cream#The cream-based dessert|snow cream]]) In these recipes, and until the end of the 19th century, naturally separated cream is whipped, typically with [[willow]] or [[Juncaceae|rush]] branches, and the resulting foam on the surface would from time to time be skimmed off and drained, a process taking an hour or more.<ref name=\"mcgee\">Harold McGee, ''On Food and Cooking'', p. 32</ref> By the end of the 19th century, [[separator (milk)|centrifuge-separated]], high-fat cream made it much faster and easier to make whipped cream.\n\nThe French name ''cr\u00e8me fouett\u00e9e'' 'whipped cream' is attested in 1629,<ref>[[Jean-Louis Guez de Balzac]], ''Lettres de Phyllarque \u00e0 Ariste'' [https://books.google.com/books?id=zW_PCX1pb80C&pg=PA370&dq=%22cr%C3%A8me+fouett%C3%A9e%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=EzsFUbXAKcfg0gGrj4CYDg&ved=0CDkQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q&f=false full text]</ref> and the English name \"whipped cream\" in 1673.<ref>{{Cite OED|whipped|id =228422}}</ref> The name \"snow cream\" continued to be used in the 17th century.<ref>''Dictionarium Rusticum, Urbanicum & Botanicum'', 1726, ''s.v.'' 'Syllabub' [https://books.google.com/books?id=v2FJAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA1-PT296 full text]</ref><ref>Sarah Harrison, ''The house-keeper's pocket-book, and compleat family cook'', 1749, p. 173. [https://books.google.com/books?id=3IcEAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA173 full text]</ref>\n\nVarious desserts consisting of whipped cream in pyramidal shapes with coffee, liqueurs, chocolate, fruits, and so on either in the mixture or poured on top were called ''cr\u00e8me en mousse'' 'cream in a foam', ''cr\u00e8me fouett\u00e9e'', ''cr\u00e8me mousseuse'' 'foamy cream', ''mousse'' 'foam',<ref name=\"emy\">M. Emy (officier), '' L'Art de bien faire les glaces d'office... avec un trait\u00e9 sur les mousses'', Paris, 1768 [https://books.google.com/books?id=qDZdAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA222 p. 222]</ref><ref>Alexandre-Balthazar-Laurent [[Grimod de La Reyni\u00e8re]], ''N\u00e9o-Physiologie du gout par order alphab\u00e9tique ou Dictionnaire g\u00e9n\u00e9rale de la cuisine fran\u00e7aise'', 1839, [https://books.google.com/books?id=ts9QAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA184 p. 184]</ref> and ''fromage \u00e0 la Chantilly'' 'Chantilly-style molded cream', as early as 1768.<ref name=\"chev\">Jim Chevallier, ''A History of the Food of Paris: From Roast Mammoth to Steak Frites'', 2018, {{isbn|1442272821}}, p. 195</ref><ref>\"Tante Marie\", ''La V\u00e9ritable cuisine de famille, comprenant 1.000 recettes et 500 menus'', 18??, [https://books.google.com/books?id=5A80_xF0vHUC&pg=PA296 p. 296] \"Cr\u00e8me fouett\u00e9e (ou Fromage \u00e0 la Chantilly)\"</ref><ref>Mrs. Beeton, ''The book of household management'', 1888, [https://books.google.com/books?id=otoAAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA927 p. 927]</ref>  Modern [[mousse]]s, including [[mousse au chocolat]], are a continuation of this tradition.\n\nCream whipped in a whipping siphon with nitrous oxide was invented in the 1930s by both Charles Getz, working with [[G. Frederick Smith]],<ref>Charles Getz, \"Process of making aerated food products\", U.S. Patent 2294172A, filed 26 September 1935, issued 25 August 1942 [http://www.google.com/patents/US2294172 full text]; also U.S. Patent 2435682 (continuation in part)</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=George Frederick Smith (1891-1976)|website=Chemistry at Illinois|publisher=University of Illinois|url=http://www.chemistry.illinois.edu/about/illini_chemists/smith.html|accessdate=2014-02-27|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131104160841/http://www.chemistry.illinois.edu/about/illini_chemists/smith.html|archivedate=2013-11-04}}</ref> and Marshall Reinecke.<ref>Marshall C. Reinecke, \"Device for producing aerated expanded food products\", U.S. Patent 2120297A, filed 15 August 1935, issued 14 June 1938 [http://www.google.com/patents/US2120297 full text]</ref> Both filed patents, which were later litigated. The Getz patents were originally deemed invalid, but were upheld on appeal.<ref name=\"lange\">Aeration Processes, Inc. ''v.'' Lange ''et al.'', 196 F.2d 981, 93 USPQ 332, United States Court of Appeals Eighth Circuit, May 20, 1952.</ref>\n\n==Cr\u00e8me Chantilly==\n\n''Cr\u00e8me Chantilly'' is another name for whipped cream. The difference between \"whipped cream\" and \"cr\u00e8me Chantilly\" is not systematic. Some authors distinguish between the two, with cr\u00e8me Chantilly being sweetened, and whipped cream not.<ref>{{cite book|chapter=Cr\u00e8me fouett\u00e9e et cr\u00e8me Chantilly|editor=Robert J. Courtine|title=Curnonsky: Cuisine et Vins de France|publisher=Larousse|year=1974|p=535}}</ref> However, most authors treat the two as synonyms,<ref name=\"robert\">{{cite book|title=[[Petit Robert|Le Petit Robert]]|year=1972|chapter=''Cr\u00e8me fouett\u00e9e'', dite aussi ''cr\u00e8me Chantilly''}}</ref> with both being sweetened,<ref name=\"grande\">''[[La Grande Encyclop\u00e9die]]'' (1902)</ref><ref>''[[Tr\u00e9sor de la langue fran\u00e7aise]]'', [http://www.cnrtl.fr/definition/cr\u00e8me ''s.v.'' cr\u00e8me]</ref> neither being sweetened,<ref name=\"dubois\">\u00c9mile Bernard Urbain Dubois, ''La Cuisine classique: \u00e9tudes pratiques, raisonn\u00e9es et d\u00e9monstratives de l'Ecole fran\u00e7aise appliqu\u00e9e au service \u00e0 la russe'', 1868, [https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_A7DX5_x_hrAC/page/n144 p. 122]: \"La chantilly n'est autre chose que la cr\u00e8me double, amen\u00e9e \u00e0 consistance, et rendue mousseuse par le travail du fouet et l'action de l'air.\"</ref><ref name=\"bocuse\">[[Paul Bocuse]], ''La cuisine du march\u00e9'' (1980), p. 414: \"Cr\u00e8me Chantilly (cr\u00e8me fouett\u00e9e)\"</ref> or treating sweetening as optional.<ref name=\"saint-ange\">''[[La cuisine de Madame Saint-Ange]]'' (1927), p. 916''f'': \"Cr\u00e8me fouett\u00e9e dite \u00ab cr\u00e8me Chantilly \u00bb... Selon le cas, on ajoute du sucre en poudre, vanill\u00e9 ou non, dans la cr\u00e8me fouett\u00e9e.\"</ref><ref>Julia Child ''et al.'', ''Mastering the Art of French Cooking'', defines ''Cr\u00e8me Chantilly'' as \"lightly beaten cream\", then refers to it as \"whipped cream\".  With added sugar or flavorings,  she calls it \"Flavored whipped cream\" ('''I''':580). In volume 2, one recipe for ''cr\u00e8me Chantilly'' is unsweetened ('''II''':422), another is sweetened ('''II''':450).</ref> Many authors use only one of the two names (for the sweetened or unsweetened version), so it is not clear if they distinguish the two.<ref>[[Larousse du XIXe]] (1878) et le [[Littr\u00e9]] (1872) mention only whipped (fouett\u00e9e); le [[Larousse Gastronomique]] (1938) mentions only Chantilly</ref>\n\nThe invention of cr\u00e8me Chantilly is often credited incorrectly, and without evidence, to [[Fran\u00e7ois Vatel]], ''[[ma\u00eetre d'h\u00f4tel]]'' at the [[Ch\u00e2teau de Chantilly]] in the mid-17th century.<ref>{{cite book|author=Stephen Shapiro|chapter=Roland Joff\u00e9's ''Vatel''|editor=Anne L. Birberick|editor2=Russell Ganim|title=Modern Perspectives on the Early Modern: Temps recherch\u00e9, temps retrouv\u00e9|year=2005|ISBN=1-886365-54-7|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=QtjJxJoXx5MC&pg=PA84 84]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.domainedechantilly.com/domaine-de-chantilly/cr%C3%A8me-chantilly/histoire-de-la-cr%C3%A8me-chantilly|title=Histoire de la Cr\u00e8me Chantilly|website=Domaine de Chantilly|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130416042751/http://www.domainedechantilly.com/domaine-de-chantilly/cr%C3%A8me-chantilly/histoire-de-la-cr%C3%A8me-chantilly|archive-date=2013-04-16}}</ref> But the name Chantilly is first connected with whipped cream in the mid-18th century,<ref>{{cite book|chapter=Fromage \u00e0 la chantilly glac\u00e9|language=fr|trans-chapter=Ice cream whipped cheese|editor=[[Menon (cookbook author)|Menon]]|title=Les soupers de la cour|trans-title=Court suppers|year=1755|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=dTI7AAAAcAAJ&pg=PA313&lpg=PA313 313-314]}}</ref> around the time that the [[Baronne d'Oberkirch]] praised the \"cream\" served at a lunch at the [[Hameau de Chantilly]]&mdash;but did not say what exactly it was, or call it Chantilly cream.<ref>{{cite book|title=M\u00e9moires de la baronne d'Oberkirch|volume=2|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=AMdCAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA112 112]|chapter=Jamais je n'ai mang\u00e9 d'aussi bonne cr\u00e8me, aussi app\u00e9tissante et aussi bien appr\u00eat\u00e9e|quote=I have never eaten such good cream, so appetising and so well prepared}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.institut-de-france.fr/minisite/tables/71_la_naissance_de_la_creme_chantilly.html|title=Naissance de la cr\u00e8me Chantilly|work=Tables princi\u00e8res \u00e0 Chantilly, du XVIIe au XIXe si\u00e8cle|language=fr|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110613140832/http://www.institut-de-france.fr/minisite/tables/71_la_naissance_de_la_creme_chantilly.html|archive-date=2011-06-13}} {{cite book|location=[[Mus\u00e9e Cond\u00e9]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081115004842/http://www.chateaudechantilly.com/pdf/DP2_tables_princieres.pdf|archive-date=2008-11-15|url=http://www.chateaudechantilly.com/pdf/DP2_tables_princieres.pdf|title=Exposition du 16 septembre 2006 au 8 janvier 2007 \u2014 Tables princi\u00e8res \u00e0 Chantilly, du XVIIe au XIXe si\u00e8cle|language=fr|trans-title=Exhibition from September 16, 2006 to January 8, 2007 \u2014 Princely tables in Chantilly, from the 17th to the 19th century|publisher=Fondation pour la sauvegarde et le d\u00e9veloppement du domaine de Chantilly}}</ref>\n\nThe names \"cr\u00e8me Chantilly\", \"cr\u00e8me de Chantilly\", \"cr\u00e8me \u00e0 la Chantilly\", or \"cr\u00e8me fouett\u00e9e \u00e0 la Chantilly\" only become common in the 19th century. In 1806, the first edition of Viard's ''[[Le Cuisinier Imp\u00e9rial|Cuisinier Imp\u00e9rial]]'' mentions neither \"whipped\" nor \"Chantilly\" cream,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sI4EAAAAYAAJ|title=Le cuisinier imp\u00e9rial, ou, L'art de faire la cuisine et la p\u00e2tisserie pour toutes les fortunes: avec diff\u00e9rentes recettes d'office et de fruits confits, et la mani\u00e8re de servir une table depuis vingt jusqu'\u00e0 soixante couverts|first=A.|last=Viard|date=1806|publisher=Barba|via=Google Books}}</ref> but the 1820 edition mentions both.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_6B5fVHfmd8kC|title=Le cuisinier royal: ou l'Art de faire la cuisine, la patisserie et tout ce qui concerne l'office, pour toutes les fortunes|first1=A.|last1=Viard|last2=Fouret|date=1820|publisher=J.-N. Barba|via=Internet Archive}}</ref>\n\nThe name ''Chantilly'' was probably used because the ch\u00e2teau had become a symbol of refined food.<ref>[[Alan Davidson (food writer)|Alan Davidson]], ''[[The Oxford Companion to Food]]'', ''s.v.'' 'cream'.</ref>\n\n==Imitation whipped cream==\nImitations of whipped cream, often sold under the name '''whipped topping''' or '''squirty cream''', are commercially available. They may be used to avoid [[dairy]] ingredients, to provide extended shelf life, or to reduce the price (although some popular brands cost twice as much as whipped cream).<ref>{{cite web|author=Patrick Di Justo|title=Cool Whip|work=[[Wired Magazine|Wired]]|date=April 24, 2007|url=https://www.wired.com/wired/archive/15.05/st_coolwhip.html}}</ref>\n\nArtificial whipped topping normally contains some mixture of [[partially hydrogenated]] oil, sweeteners, water, and stabilizers and emulsifiers added to prevent [[Syneresis (chemistry)|syneresis]].\n\nIt may be sold frozen in plastic tubs (''e.g.'', [[Cool Whip]]), or in aerosol containers or in liquid form in cartons, reminiscent of real whipping cream.\n\n==Uses==\nWhipped cream or ''cr\u00e8me Chantilly'' is a popular topping for fruit and [[dessert]]s such as pie, [[ice cream]] (especially [[sundae]]s), cupcakes, cakes, [[milkshake]]s, [[waffle]]s, [[hot chocolate]], [[cheesecake]]s, [[Jello]] and [[pudding]]s. It is also [[List of coffee drinks#Coffee or espresso with whipped cream|served on coffee]], especially in the [[Viennese coffee house]] tradition, where coffee with whipped cream is known as ''Melange mit Schlagobers''. Whipped cream is used as an ingredient in many desserts, for example as a filling for [[profiterole]]s and [[layer cake]]s.<ref>{{cite book|author=Wayne Gisslen|title=Professional Baking|year=2012|ISBN=1118254368|p=260}}</ref>\n\nIt is often piped onto a dish using a [[pastry bag]] to create decorative shapes.\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Food}}\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Alcohol-infused whipped cream]]\n* [[Dream Whip]]{{spaced ndash}} a powdered dessert topping mix\n* ''[[Schlagobers]]''{{spaced ndash}} [[Richard Strauss]]' \"Whipped Cream\" ballet\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Dairy products]]\n[[Category:Desserts]]\n", "name_user": "24.239.192.147", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Added content)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Whipped_cream"}
